  "prompt": "What is the process to get a brand name trademarked in India?",
  "response": "Trademarking a brand name in India is a systematic process that involves several steps to ensure that your brand is protected legally. Here's a detailed overview of the process:\n\n1. **Trademark Search**: \n   - Conduct a thorough search to ensure that the brand name is not already registered or pending registration. This is crucial to avoid future legal disputes. You can perform the search using the Indian Trademark Registry's online database.\n\n2. **Selection of Class**:\n   - Trademarks are categorized into 45 different classes according to the Nice Classification. Each class represents a particular type of goods or services. Determine the correct class (or classes) under which your brand should be registered.\n\n3. **Filing the Application**:\n   - Prepare and file the trademark application with the required details such as the applicant's name, address, business type, and the trademark to be registered. Include a representation of the trademark along with a list of goods/services for which the trademark is sought.\n   - Applications can be filed online through the official Trademark Registry portal or physically at the appropriate Trademark Registrar Office.\n   - If filing online, you can use Form TM-A. There might be different formats if you're registering a collective mark, series mark, or certification mark.\n\n4. **Acknowledgment and Examination**:\n   - After filing, you will receive an acknowledgment with an application number. The application is then examined by the Trademark Examiner.\n   - The examiner checks for any discrepancies and issues an examination report usually within 3-6 months.\n\n5. **Response to Examination Report (if required)**:\n   - If there are objections, you must respond to the examination report, addressing the concerns raised, within the stipulated time frame (typically 30 days).\n\n6. **Publication in the Trademark Journal**:\n   - If the application is accepted by the registrar, or if objections are overcome, the trademark is published in the Trademark Journal. This is to allow any third party to oppose the registration.\n\n7. **Opposition Period**:\n   - The trademark remains open to opposition by any third party for a period of four months from the date of publication. If opposed, both parties are required to appear for hearings, and the Registrar decides the outcome.\n   - If no opposition is filed, or if the opposition is resolved in favor of the applicant, the trademark proceeds to registration.\n\n8. **Registration**:\n   - Once the opposition period is past, and if no opposition is sustained, the trademark is registered, and a registration certificate is issued. The registered brand name is now legally protected.\n\n9. **Validity and Renewal**:\n   - A registered trademark in India is valid for 10 years from the date of application. It can be renewed indefinitely by filing a renewal application every 10 years.\n\nIt is advisable to consult with a trademark attorney throughout the process to handle any legal complexities and to ensure that all procedures are correctly followed.",
